      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for hemolysis index QoI across three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "Three meshes (3.2M, 6.8M, 14.1M cells) were generated with refinement ratio ~1.45. GCI for the scalar stress-weighted hemolysis index was 3.1% between medium and fine meshes, satisfying the < 5% criterion. Richardson extrapolation confirms asymptotic convergence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) match simulated conditions within ±5% for all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "FDA bench test data report flow rates of 2–6 L/min and speeds of 2000–3500 RPM. CFD boundary conditions replicate these within 2.3% for flow rate and 0.8% for speed. Fluid viscosity matched using bovine blood analog at 37°C."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) within ±25% of experimental measurements across all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH values ranged from 0.0021 to 0.0078 g/100L. Experimental NIH from FDA pump testing ranged 0.0019–0.0082 g/100L. Maximum deviation was 18.4% at the 6 L/min, 3500 RPM condition. All five points within acceptance band."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) directly maps to the clinical endpoint; the scalar stress-based hemolysis model output is a recognized surrogate per FDA guidance.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate is the direct regulatory decision metric. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model provides RH as primary output. FDA has accepted this QoI formulation in prior 510(k) submissions for Class II blood-contacting devices."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
